How many paths are there from $A$ to $B$ on the lines of the grid shown, if every step must be up or to the right?[asy]size(3cm,3cm);int w=6;int h=3;int i;for (i=0; i<h; ++i){ draw((0,i) -- (w-1,i));}for (i=0; i<w; ++i){ draw((i, 0)--(i,h-1));}label("$B$", (w-1,h-1), NE);label("$A$", (0,0), SW);[/asy]
For example, here is one such valid path highlighted in blue:
[asy]
size(3cm,3cm);
int w=6;
int h=3;
int i;
for (i=0; i<h; ++i){ 
draw((0,i) -- (w-1,i));
}for (i=0; i<w; ++i){ 
draw((i, 0)--(i,h-1));
}
label("$B$", (w-1,h-1), NE);
label("$A$", (0,0), SW);

draw((0,0)--(1,0), blue+1.5);
draw((1,0)--(1,1), blue+1.5);
draw((1,1)--(2,1), blue+1.5);
draw((2,1)--(3,1), blue+1.5);
draw((3,1)--(4,1), blue+1.5);
draw((4,1)--(4,2), blue+1.5);
draw((4,2)--(5,2), blue+1.5);
[/asy]

In order to get from $A$ to $B$, we need to move $w+h-2$ times: $h-1$ up and $w-1$ right. Hence, the number of paths is the number of ways to choose which of the $w+h-2$ moves are up. That is, we need to choose $h-1$ out of a total of $w+h-2$ moves to be up, which can be done in  $\binom{(w+h-2)}{(h-1)}$ ways.
Final Answer: \boxed{$\binom{(w+h-2)}{(h-1)} = \frac{(w+h-2)!}{(h-1)!(w-1)!}$. I hope it is correct.}
